│ An LLVM `slp-vectorizer` maintainer would approach this bug by first understanding the     │
│ context from the backtrace and the assertion message. The assertion `(I->use_empty() ||    │
│ all_of(I->uses(), ...)) && "trying to erase instruction with users."` in                   │
│ `removeInstructionsAndOperands` indicates an attempt to delete an instruction that still   │
│ has live users. The backtrace reveals this happens during a horizontal reduction           │
│ (`HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce`).                                                      │
│                                                                                            │
│ The key is to identify which instruction (`I`) is causing the failure and why its users    │
│ haven't been properly handled. Using the debugger is crucial here.                         │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### Debugging Steps:                                                                       │
│                                                                                            │
│ 1.  **Identify the faulty instruction**: At the crash site in                              │
│ `removeInstructionsAndOperands`, inspect the instruction `I`.                              │
│     ```gdb                                                                                 │
│     (gdb) p *I                                                                             │
│     ```                                                                                    │
│     This reveals `I` is `%tobool.not.not509.i.2329.i.i = icmp ne i32 0, 0`.                │
│                                                                                            │
│ 2.  **Inspect its users**: Check the users of this instruction.                            │
│     ```gdb                                                                                 │
│     (gdb) p I->dump()                                                                      │
│     (gdb) p I->user_back()->dump()                                                         │
│     ```                                                                                    │
│     The user is `%storemerge.2333.i.i = select i1 %tobool.not.not509.i.2329.i.i, i32 0,    │
│ i32 0`.                                                                                    │
│                                                                                            │
│ 3.  **Check the user's status**: Is the user marked for deletion?                          │
│     ```gdb                                                                                 │
│     (gdb) p isDeleted(I->user_back())                                                      │
│     ```                                                                                    │
│     The result is `false`, which confirms why the assertion fails: we are trying to delete │
│ `%tobool.not.not509.i.2329.i.i` while its user `%storemerge.2333.i.i` is still live.       │
│                                                                                            │
│ 4.  **Analyze the vectorization plan**: Why wasn't the user instruction included in the    │
│ vectorized tree or otherwise handled? The `SLP` debug logs show that the vectorizer        │
│ identified a horizontal reduction involving a chain of `select` instructions. The          │
│ vectorizer decided to build a vector from several `icmp` instructions. The instruction     │
│ `%tobool.not.not509.i.2329.i.i` was part of the plan, but its user `%storemerge.2333.i.i`  │
│ was not.                                                                                   │
│                                                                                            │
│ 5.  **Root Cause Analysis**: The problem lies in how the horizontal reduction logic        │
│ collects instructions. The function `HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce` builds a            │
│ `VectorizedTree` containing the instructions to be vectorized and then erased. In this     │
│ case, it correctly identifies a set of `icmp` instructions to merge. However, it fails to  │
│ recognize that one of these `icmp` instructions (`%tobool.not.not509.i.2329.i.i`) has a    │
│ user (`%storemerge.2333.i.i`) that is *part of the reduction chain itself* but is not      │
│ included in the set of vectorized instructions.                                            │
│                                                                                            │
│     The core of the issue is in `BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree`. When it prepares to erase the    │
│ scalar instructions, it doesn't account for users that are part of the same logical        │
│ operation but are not inside the `VectorizedTree`. The `select` instruction                │
│ `%storemerge.2333.i.i` is an intermediate value in the reduction chain that the vectorizer │
│ is trying to optimize. The vectorizer correctly identifies the leaf `icmp`s for            │
│ vectorization but misses adding this intermediate `select` to the set of instructions to   │
│ be deleted.                                                                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### Proposed Fix                                                                           │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to ensure that when an instruction is added to the `VectorizedTree` for a       │
│ horizontal reduction, its users that are part of the reduction are also correctly          │
│ processed. A simple way to handle this specific case is to add the user to the             │
│ `VectorizedTree` if it's a `select` instruction that will become dead after vectorization. │
│                                                                                            │
│ The logic in `BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree` should be amended. Before erasing scalars, we can    │
│ perform an extra check. For each instruction in `VectorizedTree`, if it has users that are │
│ not in the tree, we should check if those users can be safely added.                       │
│                                                                                            │
│ A targeted fix would be to modify `BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree` to identify and include such    │
│ "dangling" users from the reduction chain into the set of instructions to be erased.       │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│ // In BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree, before erasing scalars:                                      │
│ for (Instruction *I : VectorizedTree) {                                                    │
│   if (isDeleted(I))                                                                        │
│     continue;                                                                              │
│   for (User *U : I->users()) {                                                             │
│     if (auto *UserInst = dyn_cast<Instruction>(U)) {                                       │
│       if (!isDeleted(UserInst) && !VectorizedVals.count(UserInst) &&                       │
│           is_safe_to_delete(UserInst)) { // is_safe_to_delete would check if all other     │
│ operands are constants or part of the tree                                                 │
│         eraseInstruction(UserInst);                                                        │
│       }                                                                                    │
│     }                                                                                      │
│   }                                                                                        │
│ }                                                                                          │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ However, a more robust fix would be within the horizontal reduction analysis itself,       │
│ ensuring the `VectorizedTree` is complete. The analysis should recognize that              │
│ `%storemerge.2333.i.i` is an essential part of the reduction structure and include it.     │
│                                                                                            │
│ Looking at the code for `HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce`, it seems it focuses on finding │
│ a chain of similar operations. The interaction between the `icmp` and the `select` might   │
│ be a pattern it doesn't fully handle.                                                      │
│                                                                                            │
