│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                                            │
│ ### 1. Understanding the Issue                                                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ The SLP vectorizer is aborting due to an assertion failure in the                          │
│ `removeInstructionsAndOperands` function. The assertion `(I->use_empty() ||                │
│ all_of(I->uses(), ...))` fails because an attempt is made to delete an instruction that    │
│ still has users not marked for deletion. This points to an incomplete analysis by the      │
│ vectorizer, where it fails to account for all consequences of its transformations, which   │
│ could lead to invalid IR.                                                                  │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log and Debugger State                                            │
│                                                                                            │
│ - **Backtrace**: The call stack clearly indicates the crash happens during the             │
│ vectorization of a horizontal reduction, originating from                                  │
│ `HorizontalReduction::tryToReduce` which calls `vectorizeTree`, and finally                │
│ `removeInstructionsAndOperands` where the assertion is triggered.                          │
│ - **`opt` Log**: The log corroborates the backtrace, showing the vectorizer identifying    │
│ and attempting to vectorize a horizontal reduction (`SLP: Vectorizing horizontal reduction │
│ at cost:-5. (HorRdx)`). The subsequent log entries show the process of scheduling and then │
│ erasing scalar instructions, which is where the process fails.                             │
│ - **Debugger Inspection**:                                                                 │
│     - At the crash site (frame 1), I inspected the instruction `I` that is being deleted.  │
│ It is `%cmp80.1.2.i.i193`.                                                                 │
│     - I checked its users and found it is used by `%cmp80.1.2.i.i`.                        │
│     - A call to `isDeleted(I->user_back())` returned `false`, confirming that this user    │
│ instruction was not part of the set of instructions to be deleted. This is the direct      │
│ violation of the assertion.                                                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 3. Root Cause Analysis                                                                 │
│                                                                                            │
│ The core problem is that the horizontal reduction analysis identifies a set of scalar      │
│ instructions to vectorize (`Scalars`, which comes from `VectorizedTree`) but fails to      │
│ include all instructions that become redundant as a result. In this specific case, the     │
│ instruction `%cmp80.1.2.i.i193` is part of the `VectorizedTree`. Its user,                 │
│ `%cmp80.1.2.i.i`, is a `select` instruction that is part of the reduction chain. While     │
│ other parts of this chain are vectorized, this specific `select` is missed. After          │
│ vectorization, the new vector code effectively bypasses this `select`, rendering it dead.  │
│ However, because it was not added to the `VectorizedTree` or any other list of             │
│ instructions to be deleted, it remains in the IR, holding a use of `%cmp80.1.2.i.i193`.    │
│ When the vectorizer tries to erase `%cmp80.1.2.i.i193`, the assertion correctly fires.     │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ To fix this, the vectorizer must be more thorough in cleaning up instructions that become  │
│ dead after it transforms the code. The most appropriate place to add this logic is in      │
│ `BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree`, just before the original scalar instructions are erased at line  │
│ 16145.                                                                                     │
│                                                                                            │
│ My proposed solution is to iterate through the instructions in `Scalars` and inspect their │
│ users. If a user is an instruction that is *not* in the `VectorizedTree` but all of *its*  │
│ users *are* in the `VectorizedTree` (or already marked for deletion), then this            │
│ intermediate instruction has become dead and can be safely erased. I will add a loop that  │
│ collects these newly-dead instructions (`DeadUsers`) and then calls                        │
│ `removeInstructionsAndOperands` on them before proceeding with the main cleanup of the     │
│ `Scalars` themselves.                                                                      │
│                                                                                            │
│ I will replace line 16145 of `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp` with the    │
│ following code block:                                                                      │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│   // Collect and erase instructions that will become dead because their users are          │
│   // all part of the vectorized tree.                                                      │
│   SmallVector<Instruction *, 8> DeadUsers;                                                 │
│   for (Instruction *I : Scalars) {                                                         │
│     // If the instruction is already marked for deletion, we don't need to check it.       │
│     if (isDeleted(I))                                                                      │
│       continue;                                                                            │
│                                                                                            │
│     for (User *U : I->users()) {                                                           │
│       auto *UI = dyn_cast<Instruction>(U);                                                 │
│       // Check if the user is a valid instruction, not already planned for deletion,       │
│       // and not part of the main vectorized values.                                       │
│       if (!UI || isDeleted(UI) || VectorizedVals.count(UI))                                │
│         continue;                                                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│       // An instruction is considered dead if all of its users are part of the             │
│       // vectorized tree (or are already marked for deletion).                             │
│       bool AllUsersInTree = true;                                                          │
│       if (!UI->use_empty()) {                                                              │
│         for (User *UU : UI->users()) {                                                     │
│           auto *UUI = cast<Instruction>(UU);                                               │
│           if (!isDeleted(UUI) && !VectorizedVals.count(UUI)) {                             │
│             AllUsersInTree = false;                                                        │
│             break;                                                                         │
│           }                                                                                │
│         }                                                                                  │
│       }                                                                                    │
│                                                                                            │
│       if (AllUsersInTree) {                                                                │
│         DeadUsers.push_back(UI);                                                           │
│       }                                                                                    │
│     }                                                                                      │
│   }                                                                                        │
│   removeInstructionsAndOperands(DeadUsers);                                                │
│                                                                                            │
│   removeInstructionsAndOperands(Scalars);                                                  │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 5. Conclusion                                                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ The bug is caused by an incomplete accounting of dead instructions following a horizontal  │
│ reduction transformation. The fix involves adding a cleanup step to `vectorizeTree` that   │
│ identifies and removes these newly dead instructions before the original vectorized        │
│ scalars are erased. This ensures that no dangling uses remain, thus satisfying the         │
│ assertion and preventing the crash.                                                        │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                            │
