│ An assertion failure in the SLP vectorizer's `removeInstructionsAndOperands` function      │
│ indicates that an instruction is being deleted while it still has users. This typically    │
│ occurs when the vectorizer's analysis does not correctly identify all instructions that    │
│ become dead after a transformation.                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ In this specific case, the crash happens during the vectorization of a horizontal          │
│ reduction. The vectorizer correctly identifies a set of scalar instructions to vectorize   │
│ and replace with vector operations. However, it fails to account for certain intermediate  │
│ instructions that use these scalars. After the transformation, these intermediate          │
│ instructions become dead code, but since they are not marked for deletion, they still hold │
│ references to the original scalar instructions. When the vectorizer attempts to clean up   │
│ by deleting the now-redundant scalar instructions, the assertion is triggered because      │
│ these dead-but-not-deleted instructions are still users.                                   │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to introduce an additional cleanup step within the `BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree`     │
│ function, which is responsible for the vectorization process. Before deleting the original │
│ scalar instructions, we will iterate through them and inspect their users. If a user       │
│ instruction is not part of the vectorized tree but all of its own users are, it implies    │
│ this user has become dead as a result of the vectorization. By identifying and collecting  │
│ these newly-dead instructions and explicitly marking them for deletion, we ensure that no  │
│ dangling uses remain, thus preventing the assertion failure.                               │
│                                                                                            │
│ This change is implemented by adding a loop that identifies these dead user instructions   │
│ and then calls `removeInstructionsAndOperands` on them, just before the original           │
